      <div class="fraction-carousel">
        <div class="fraction-lesson active">
          <!-- Content for the upper and lower parts of fractions using pizza examples -->
          <h2>Understanding Fractions</h2>
          <p>Fractions have two parts. The upper (Numerator) and the lower (Denominator), seperated by a line. </p>
          <p> One way of visualizing fractions would be to look at a pizza that has 8 slices. </p>
          <img src="../../assets/pizza_8-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="8-Pizza-Slices">
            <p>If we have 3 out of 8 possible slices of a pizza, we can represent it as
              <sup>3</sup>/<sub>8</sub>.
            </p>
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_3-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="3-Pizza-Slices">
  
        </div>
        <div class="fraction-lesson ">
          <!-- Content for the upper and lower parts of fractions using pizza examples -->
          <h2>Understanding Fractions</h2>
         
        
          <p>You can also have a larger upper number( Numerator) than lower (Denominator), which means the total is more than 1. </p>
          <p>Example:
          (10 slices pizza) is equal to 1 whole 8-slice pizza plus 
          2 extra slices:
          <sup>10</sup>/<sub>8</sub>  =   <sup>8</sup>/<sub>8</sub> + <sup>2</sup>/<sub>8</sub>.
          <img src="../../assets/pizza_8-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="8-Pizza-Slices">
          <img src="../../assets/pizza_2-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="2-Pizza-Slices">

          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="fraction-lesson">
          <!-- Content for comparing fractions using pizza examples -->
          <h2>Comparing Fractions</h2>
          <p>When comparing fractions, if the lower number (Denominator) is the same for both fractions. then you can simply compare the top two numbers.</p>
        
  
          <p>For example, if we have <sup>3</sup>/<sub>8</sub> of a pizza and our friend has <sup>2</sup>/<sub>8</sub>
            of a pizza, we can see that our fraction of the pizza is larger because we have more slices.</p>
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_3-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="3-Pizza-Slices">
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_2-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="2-Pizza-Slices">
        </div>
       
        <div class="fraction-lesson">
          <!-- Content for comparing fractions using pizza examples -->
          <h2>Equal Fractions</h2>
          <p>The same fraction can be represented in  different ways, and still equal the same amount.</p>
  
          <p>Eexample, if we have 4 slices (<sup>4</sup>/<sub>8</sub>) of a pizza, we could also say we have half (<sup>1</sup>/<sub>2</sub>) of a pizza.  </p>

          <img src="../../assets/pizza_4-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="4-Pizza-Slices">
<p>
            Both fractions are equivalent, or equal. If you multiply (or divide) the top and bottom parts of a fraction by the same number the result is equal in value.
           </p>
        </div>
        <div class="fraction-lesson">
          <!-- Content for adding fractions using pizza examples -->
          <h2>Adding Fractions</h2>
          <p>When adding fractions, we have to have the same common denominator (same lower number) Then you can simply add the two top numbers.</p>
   
  
          <p>Example: If we have 1 slice  (<sup>1</sup>/<sub>8</sub>) of a pizza and we then have two (<sup>2</sup>/<sub>8</sub>) of
            another pizza, we get a total of 3 slices (<sup>3</sup>/<sub>8</sub>).</p>
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_1-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="1-Pizza-Slices">
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_2-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="2-Pizza-Slices">
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_3-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="3-Pizza-Slices">
        </div>
  
        <div class="fraction-lesson">
          <!-- Content for subtracting fractions using pizza examples -->
          <h2>Subtracting Fractions</h2>
          <p>When subtracting  fractions, we have to have the same common denominator (Same lower number). Then you can simply subtract the top numbers.</p>
        
          <p>Example: If we have 5 slices (<sup>5</sup>/<sub>8</sub>) of a pizza and we give 2 slices away ( <sup>2</sup>/<sub>8</sub>), 
             we are left with 3 slices ( <sup>3</sup>/<sub>8</sub>).</p>
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_5-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="5-Pizza-Slices">
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_2-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="2-Pizza-Slices">
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_3-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="3-Pizza-Slices">
    
        </div>
  
        <div class="fraction-lesson">
          <!-- Content for multiplying fractions using pizza examples -->
          <h2>Multiplying Fractions</h2>
          <p>When multiplying fractions, you multiply the top parts together, and you multiply the bottom parts together.</p>
      
  
          <p>For example, if we have 2 slice of pizza (<sup>2</sup>/<sub>8</sub>) of a pizza and we want 3 times that amount ( 3 or
            <sup>3</sup>/<sub>1</sub>), we get a total of 6 slices <sup>6</sup>/<sub>8</sub> slices.
          </p>
          <img src="../../assets/pizza_2-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="2-Pizza-Slices">
          <img src="../../assets/pizza_6-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="6-Pizza-Slices">
        </div>
  
        <div class="fraction-lesson">
          <!-- Content for dividing fractions using pizza examples -->
          <h2>Dividing Fractions</h2>
          <p>When dividing fractions by a number, you can divide the Numerator (top) by that number.</p>

  
          <p>For example, if we have <sup>8</sup>/<sub>8</sub> of a pizza and we divide it equally among 2 people, each
            person will have <sup>4</sup>/<sub>8</sub> of the pizza.</p>
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_8-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="8-Pizza-Slices">
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_4-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="4-Pizza-Slices">
        </div>

        <div class="fraction-lesson">
          <!-- Content for comparing fractions using pizza examples -->
          <h2>Working with Fractions</h2>
          <p>If the denominator (lower number) is different for two fractions, and we want to compare of perform addition/subtraction, we have to find a 'Common Denominator'.</p>

  
          <p>For example, if we have half ( <sup>1</sup>/<sub>2</sub>) of a pizza and our friend has a quarter of the pizza (<sup>1</sup>/<sub>8</sub>)
            we would need to find the lowest common denominator to add the two. </p>
            <p> How: <sup>1</sup>/<sub>2</sub> could also be written as  <sup>4</sup>/<sub>8</sub> since they are equal to eachother.  Since <sup>4</sup>/<sub>8</sub>  and <sup>1</sup>/<sub>8</sub>  have the same common denominator of 8, they can be added easily to make<sup>5</sup>/<sub>8</sub> </p>
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_4-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="4-Pizza-Slices">
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_1-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="1-Pizza-Slices">
            <img src="../../assets/pizza_5-r.png" width="80" height="80" alt="5-Pizza-Slices">
          </div>
